I personally prefer the null value to flag values like these ones.
If you or @ywangd  think otherwise, I'll go with that.

I would choose null over the static exception as well. Afterall, the original error from ReservedRealm is null.
Alternatively, if we wanna have some brainstorming here, we could give the IteratingActionListener a non-default iterationPredicate so it can terminate earlier even with a null user response, e.g. something like the follows:
final AtomicBoolean terminated = new AtomicBoolean(false);
final BiConsumer<Realm, ActionListener<User>> realmAuthenticatingConsumer = (realm, userListener) -> {
   ...
   if (request.getException() == null) {
        logger.info(...);
        terminated.set(true);
        userListener.onResponse(null)
   } else {
        logger.info(...);
        userListener.onFailure(request.getException());
   }
   ...
};
...
final IteratingActionListener<User, Realm> authenticatingListener =
    new IteratingActionListener<>(..., 
        Function.identity(), 
        user -> Objects.isNull(user) && terminated.get() == false);
Yet another option is to have a static NOT_AUTHENTICATED_USER object as a static field in User class and use it to signal earlier termination:
   if (request.getException() == null) {
        logger.info(...);
        userListener.onResponse(User.NOT_AUTHENTICATED_USER)
   } else {
        logger.info(...);
        userListener.onFailure(request.getException());
   }
In consumeUser(), we will then need to check both null and this object, i.e.
if (user == null || user == User.NOT_AUTHENTICATED_USER) { ... }
Or we could give IteratingActionListener a transform function of response -> null ? User.NOT_AUTHENTICATED_USER : response so that consumeUser() can drop the null check.
Both of the alternatives reuse the logic in consumeUser, but add complexity elsewhere. I don't think they are better, just different choices. I personally would probably go with the static User field approach, but the null exception approach is fine with me.
